      "questionText": "Solve $\\dfrac{2x+3}{4} - \\dfrac{x-1}{3} = 2$.",
      "answerType": "numeric",
      "correctAnswer": "5.5",
      "tolerance": 0.05,
      "unit": null,
      "markScheme": [
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "Multiply throughout by 12 (LCM of 4 and 3)" },
        { "mark": "M1", "desc": "$3(2x+3) - 4(x-1) = 24 \\Rightarrow 2x+13=24$" },
        { "mark": "A1", "desc": "$x = 5.5$ cao" }
      ],
      "workingSteps": [
        "Multiply by 12: $3(2x+3) - 4(x-1) = 24$",
        "$6x+9-4x+4 = 24$",
        "$2x+13 = 24$",
        "$2x = 11 \\Rightarrow x = 5.5$",
        "Check: $\\frac{2(5.5)+3}{4}-\\frac{5.5-1}{3}=\\frac{14}{4}-\\frac{4.5}{3}=3.5-1.5=2$ ✓"
      ],
      "explanation": "Multiply every term by the LCM of the denominators to clear the fractions."
    },
